# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: boston
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:boston/1776-book] The text closely mirrors the original book, but omits or summarizes some parts deemed too long.
[src:boston/1776-book] The Illustrated Edition comes with its own protective slipcase, decorated with *The Capture of the Hessians at Trenton, December 26, 1776* by John Trumbull and has a "fake watermark" of the Great Seal of the United States on the back and front.
[src:boston/1776-book] The book is plain covered in blue with the golden embossed numbers "1776".
[src:boston/1790-united-states-census] The **1790 United States census** was the first United States census.
[src:boston/1790-united-states-census] It recorded the population of the whole United States as of Census Day, August 2, 1790, as mandated by Article 1, Section 2, of the Constitution and applicable laws.
[src:boston/1790-united-states-census] In the first census, the population of the United States was enumerated to be 3,929,214 inhabitants.
[src:boston/1790-united-states-census] Congress assigned responsibility for the 1790 census to the marshals of United States judicial districts under an act, which with minor modifications and extensions, governed census taking through the 1840 census.
[src:boston/1790-united-states-census] Both Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson and President George Washington expressed skepticism over the results, believing that the true population had been undercounted.
[src:boston/1790-united-states-census] If indeed an undercount was the result, possible explanations for it include dispersed population, poor transportation links, limitations of contemporary technology, and individual refusal to participate.
[src:boston/1790-united-states-census] Although the census was proved statistically factual, based on data collected, the records for several states (including Delaware, Georgia, New Jersey, and Virginia) were lost sometime between 1790 and 1830.
[src:boston/1790-united-states-census] Almost one-third of the original census data have been lost or destroyed since their original documentation.
[src:boston/1790-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1790 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:boston/1790-united-states-census] The census was not conducted in Vermont until 1791, after that state's admission to the Union as the 14th state on March 4 of that year.
[src:boston/1790-united-states-census] At 17.8 percent, the 1790 census's proportion of slaves to the free population was the highest ever recorded by any census of the United States.
[src:boston/1790-united-states-census] 0 is the correct figure, and the 16 here should be added to the "All other free persons" column.
[src:boston/1790-united-states-census] When the census of 1790 was published in 1791, it reported 16 slaves, which were illegal in Vermont.
[src:boston/1790-united-states-census] Subsequently, and up to 1860, the number is given as 17.
[src:boston/1790-united-states-census] An examination of the original manuscript by the Census Bureau superintendent found that there never were any slaves in Vermont.
[src:boston/1790-united-states-census] The original error occurred in preparing the results for publication, when 16 persons, returned as "Free colored," were classified as "Slave" in Bennington County.
[src:boston/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 85,425, or 114 less than figures published in 1790, due to an error of addition of several towns.
[src:boston/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 59,096, or 2 more than figures published in 1790, due to error in addition.
[src:boston/1790-united-states-census] The figures for Virginia do not include the population of Kentucky.
[src:boston/1790-united-states-census] Though Kentucky was then a part of Virginia, the Kentucky figures were compiled separately, and are shown on the line for Kentucky.
[src:boston/1790-united-states-census] The Virginia figures do include the portion of Virginia that later became the state of West Virginia.
[src:boston/1800-united-states-census] The **1800 United States census** was the second census conducted in the United States.
[src:boston/1800-united-states-census] It showed that 5,308,483 people were living in the United States, of whom 893,602 were slaves.
[src:boston/1800-united-states-census] The 1800 census included the new District of Columbia.
[src:boston/1800-united-states-census] The census for the following states were lost: Georgia, Kentucky, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia.
[src:boston/1800-united-states-census] In comparison to the 1790 census, the 1800 census gathered additional information.
[src:boston/1800-united-states-census] The census was published in December 1801 and cost $66,109.04.
[src:boston/1800-united-states-census] This census is one of the several for which some of the original data are no longer available.
[src:boston/1800-united-states-census] Original census returns for Georgia, Kentucky, Mississippi, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia were lost over the years.
[src:boston/1800-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1800 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:boston/1810-united-states-census] The **1810 United States census** was the third census conducted in the United States.
[src:boston/1810-united-states-census] It showed that 7,239,881 people were living in the United States, of whom 1,191,362 were slaves.
[src:boston/1810-united-states-census] The 1810 census included one new state: Ohio.
[src:boston/1810-united-states-census] The original census returns for the District of Columbia, Georgia, Mississippi, New Jersey, and Ohio were lost or destroyed over the years.
[src:boston/1810-united-states-census] Most of Tennessee's original forms were also lost, other than Grainger and Rutherford counties.
[src:boston/1810-united-states-census] This was the last census with Virginia ranked as the most populous state.
[src:boston/1810-united-states-census] Census taking was not yet an exact science.
[src:boston/1810-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and some drew up their own, resulting in pages without headings.
[src:boston/1810-united-states-census] Some enumerators did not tally their results.
[src:boston/1810-united-states-census] As a result, census records for many towns before 1830 are idiosyncratic.
[src:boston/1810-united-states-census] This is not to suggest that they are less reliable than subsequent censuses, but that they may require more work on the part of the researcher.
[src:boston/1810-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1810 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:boston/1820-united-states-census] The **1820 United States census** was the fourth census conducted in the United States.
[src:boston/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census included six new states: Louisiana, Indiana, Mississippi, Illinois, Alabama and Maine.
[src:boston/1820-united-states-census] There has been a district wide loss of 1820 census records for Arkansas Territory, Missouri Territory, and New Jersey.
[src:boston/1820-united-states-census] The total population was determined to be 9,638,453, of which 1,538,022 were slaves.
[src:boston/1820-united-states-census] The center of population was about 120 miles (193 km) west-northwest of Washington in Hardy County, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:boston/1820-united-states-census] This was the first census in which any states recorded a population of over one million—New York, Virginia, and Pennsylvania—as well as the first in which a city recorded a population of over 100,000—New York.
[src:boston/1820-united-states-census] Also, in this census and the 14 subsequent ones, New York was the most populous state until being superseded by California in the 1970 census.
[src:boston/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census contains a great deal more information than previous censuses.
[src:boston/1820-united-states-census] Several of these columns were for special counts, and not to be included in the aggregate total.
[src:boston/1820-united-states-census] Doing so would have resulted in counting some individuals twice.
[src:boston/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were asked to use double lines, red ink or some other method of distinguishing these columns so that double counting would not occur.
[src:boston/1820-united-states-census] For example, the count of free white males between 16 and 18 was a special count, because these individuals were also supposed to be tabulated in the column for free white males of age 16 and under 26.
[src:boston/1820-united-states-census] The other special counts were foreigners not naturalized, persons engaged in agriculture, persons engaged in commerce, and persons engaged in manufacture.
[src:boston/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were also instructed to count each individual in only one of the occupational columns.
[src:boston/1820-united-states-census] For example, if an individual was engaged in agriculture, commerce, and manufacture, the census taker had to judge which one the individual was primarily engaged in.
[src:boston/1820-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and drew up their own, sometimes resulting in pages without headings, line tallies, or column totals.
[src:boston/1830-united-states-census] The **1830 United States census**, the fifth census undertaken in the United States, was conducted on June 1, 1830.
[src:boston/1830-united-states-census] The only loss of census records for 1830 involved some countywide losses in Massachusetts, Maryland, and Mississippi.
[src:boston/1830-united-states-census] It determined the population of the 24 states to be 12,866,020, of which 2,009,043 were slaves.
[src:boston/1830-united-states-census] The center of population was about 170 miles (274 km) west of Washington, D.C. in present-day Grant County, West Virginia.
[src:boston/1830-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York—recorded a population of over 200,000.
[src:boston/1830-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1830 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:boston/1840-united-states-census] The **1840 United States census** was the sixth census of the United States.
[src:boston/1840-united-states-census] Conducted by U.S. marshals on June 1, 1840, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 17,069,453 – an increase of 32.7 percent over the 12,866,020 persons enumerated during the 1830 census.
[src:boston/1840-united-states-census] The total population included 2,487,355 slaves.
[src:boston/1840-united-states-census] In 1840, the center of population was about 260 miles (418 km) west of Washington, D.C., near Weston, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:boston/1840-united-states-census] This was the last census conducted by U.S. marshals, as starting in 1850 a temporary office would be set up for each census under the purview of the Department of the Interior.
[src:boston/1840-united-states-census] This was due to the Northern members of the Whig Party opposing the controversial claim in the 1840 census that free Black Americans in the Northern United States suffered from a higher degree of "insane" or "idiotic" behavior compared to enslaved Black Americans.
[src:boston/1840-united-states-census] The 1840 census was the first that attempted to count Americans who were "insane" or "idiotic".
[src:boston/1840-united-states-census] Published results of the census indicated that alarming numbers of black persons living in non-slaveholding States were mentally ill, in striking contrast to the corresponding figures for slaveholding States.
[src:boston/1840-united-states-census] Pro-slavery advocates trumpeted the results as evidence of the beneficial effects of slavery, and the probable consequences of emancipation.
[src:boston/1840-united-states-census] The memorial was submitted to the House of Representatives by John Quincy Adams, who contended that it demonstrated "a multitude of gross and important errors" in the published returns.
[src:boston/1840-united-states-census] In response to the House's request for an inquiry, Secretary of State John C.
[src:boston/1840-united-states-census] Calhoun reported that a careful examination of the statistics by the supervisor of the census had fully sustained their correctness.
[src:boston/1840-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1840 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:boston/1840-united-states-census] A compendium of data from the sixth census, organized by States, counties, and principal towns is available on the web site of the Census Bureau.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Boston was founded on Shawmut Peninsula in 1630 by English Puritan settlers, who named the city after the market town of Boston, Lincolnshire, in England.
[src:boston/boston-p01] During the American Revolution and Revolutionary War, Boston was home to several seminal events, including the Boston Massacre (1770), the Boston Tea Party (1773), Paul Revere's midnight ride (1775), the Battle of Bunker Hill (1775), and the Siege of Boston (1775–1776).
[src:boston/boston-p01] Following American independence from Great Britain, Boston played an important national role as a port, manufacturing hub, and education and culture center, and the city expanded significantly beyond the original peninsula by filling in land and annexing neighboring towns.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Boston's many firsts include the nation's first public park (Boston Common, 1634), the first public school (Boston Latin School, 1635), and the first subway system (Tremont Street subway, 1897).
[src:boston/boston-p01] Boston later emerged as a global leader in higher education and research and was the largest biotechnology hub in the world as of 2023.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The city is a national leader in scientific research, law, medicine, engineering, and business.
[src:boston/boston-p01] With nearly 5,000 startup companies, the city is considered a global pioneer in innovation, entrepreneurship, and artificial intelligence.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Boston's economy is led by finance, professional and business services, information technology, and government.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The city's businesses and institutions rank among the top in the nation for environmental sustainability and new investment.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The name of the English town derives from its patron saint, St.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Botolph, in whose church Cotton served as the rector until he and Johnson emigrated to New England.
[src:boston/boston-p01] In early sources, Lincolnshire's Boston was known as "St.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Botolph's town", which was later abbreviated as "Boston".
[src:boston/boston-p01] Before this renaming, the settlement on the peninsula was known as "Shawmut" by William Blaxton and "Tremontaine" by the Puritan settlers he invited.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Before European colonization, the region surrounding present-day Boston was inhabited by the Massachusett people, who established small, seasonal communities in present-day Boston.
[src:boston/boston-p01] In 1630, settlers led by John Winthrop arrived, and found Shawmut Peninsula nearly empty of Native people.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Most had died of European diseases borne by earlier settlers and traders.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Archaeological excavations have unearthed one of the oldest fishweirs in New England, located on Boylston Street, which Native people constructed as early as 7,000 years before European arrival in the Western Hemisphere.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The first European to live in what would become Boston was a University of Cambridge-educated Anglican cleric named William Blaxton.
[src:boston/boston-p01] He was most directly responsible for the foundation of Boston by Puritan colonists in 1630, after Blaxton invited one of their leaders, Isaac Johnson, to cross Back Bay from the failing colony of Charlestown and share the peninsula with him.
[src:boston/boston-p01] In September 1630 Puritans made the crossing to present-day Boston.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Puritan influence on Boston began even before the settlement was founded with the 1629 Cambridge Agreement, which created the Massachusetts Bay Colony and was signed by the colony's first governor, John Winthrop.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Puritan ethics and their focus on education also influenced the city's early history.
[src:boston/boston-p01] In 1635, America's first public school, Boston Latin School, was founded in Boston.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Boston was the largest town in the Thirteen Colonies until Philadelphia outgrew it in the mid-18th century.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Boston's oceanfront location made it a lively port, and the town engaged in shipping and fishing during the colonial era.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Boston was a primary stop on the Caribbean trade route and imported large amounts of molasses, which led to the creation of Boston baked beans.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Boston's economy stagnated in the decades prior to the American Revolution.
[src:boston/boston-p01] By the mid-18th century, New York City and Philadelphia both surpassed Boston in wealth.
[src:boston/boston-p01] During this period, Boston encountered financial difficulties even as other New England cities were growing rapidly.
[src:boston/boston-p01] , about the British army's decision to leave Boston, dated March 21, 1776.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Boston played a central role in the American Revolution.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Many crucial events of the American Revolution and subsequent American Revolutionary War occurred in or near Boston, where the city's revolutionary spirit against Britain's colonial governance was demonstrable and ultimately inspiring to the rest of the Thirteen Colonies.
[src:boston/boston-p01] When the British Parliament passed the Stamp Act in 1765, the homes of Andrew Oliver, the official tasked with enforcing the Act, and Thomas Hutchinson, then lieutenant governor of Massachusetts Bay Colony, were raved by Boston mobs.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The British responded by sending two regiments to Boston in 1768 in an attempt to quell the revolt, but the increased British military presence in Boston only ended up further inflaming the Boston colonists.
[src:boston/boston-p01] In 1770, during the Boston Massacre, British troops fired into a Boston mob that was protesting their presence.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The massacre forced the British to withdraw their troops and helped fuel revolutionary sentiment in the colonies.
[src:boston/boston-p01] In May 1773, Parliament passed the Tea Act, which many colonists saw as a British attempt to compel them to accept taxes established by the Townshend Acts.
[src:boston/boston-p01] This led to the Boston Tea Party, a defining event of the American Revolution in which angered Bostonians threw an entire shipment of tea sent from the East India Company into Boston Harbor, escalating the American Revolution.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The British monarchy responded furiously, implementing the Intolerable Acts and demanding compensation for the tea destroyed during the Boston Tea Party.
[src:boston/boston-p01] This response, in turn, angered the colonists further, leading to the Battles of Lexington and Concord on April 19, 1775, the first battles of the American Revolutionary War, which were fought around Boston in Massachusetts Bay Colony.
[src:boston/boston-p01] During the siege of Boston from April 19, 1775, to March 17, 1776, New England-based Patriot militia impeded movement by the British Army.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Sir William Howe, then commander-in-chief of British forces in North America, led the British army in the siege.
[src:boston/boston-p01] On June 17, the British captured Charlestown in present-day Boston during the Battle of Bunker Hill during which the British Army outnumbered Patriot militia.
[src:boston/boston-p01] But the British sustained irreplaceable casualties, turning the Battle of Bunker Hill into a pyrrhic victory for the British.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The Battle of Bunker Hill also demonstrated the skill and training of the Patriot militia, whose stubborn defense made it difficult for the British to capture Charlestown without suffering even further casualties.
[src:boston/boston-p01] On June 14, 1775, in an effort to unify the Revolutionary War effort, the Second Continental Congress, convening in the colonial-era capital of Philadelphia, founded the Continental Army and unanimously appointed George Washington as its commander-in-chief.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Washington then immediately departed Philadelphia for Boston, where he arrived on July 2, 1775, and led the newly-formed Continental Army in the siege.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Fighting was limited to small-scale raids and skirmishes, and the Continental Army faced challenges with a deficiency of munitions and supplies.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Boston Neck, then narrow and only approximately 100 feet wide, impeded Washington's ability to invade Boston, which led to a prolonged stalemate between the Continental Army and British forces.
[src:boston/boston-p01] A young officer, Rufus Putnam, came up with a plan to make portable fortifications out of wood, which were erected on the frozen ground under cover of darkness.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Putnam supervised the effort, which successfully installed the fortifications and dozens of cannons on Dorchester Heights that Henry Knox laboriously brought through the snow from Fort Ticonderoga.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The following morning, the astonished British Army awoke to see a large array of cannons bearing down on them.
[src:boston/boston-p01] General Howe is believed to have said that the Americans had done more in one night than his British Army could have done in six months.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The British Army responded by attempting to launch a cannon barrage for two hours, but their shots could not reach the Continental Army's cannons at such a height.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The British then gave up, boarded their ships, and sailed away from Boston in what has come to be known as "Evacuation Day", which is now celebrated in Boston annually on March 17.
[src:boston/boston-p01] After the British retreat, Washington was so impressed with the effort of Rufus Putnam that he appointed him as his chief engineer.
[src:boston/boston-p01] After the Revolution, Boston's long seafaring tradition helped make it one of the nation's busiest ports for both domestic and international trade.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Boston's harbor activity was significantly curtailed by the Embargo Act of 1807, which was adopted during the Napoleonic Wars, and the War of 1812.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Foreign trade returned after these hostilities, but Boston's merchants had found alternatives for their capital investments in the meantime.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Manufacturing became an important component of the city's economy, and the city's industrial manufacturing overtook international trade in economic importance by the mid-19th century.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The small rivers bordering the city and connecting it to the surrounding region facilitated shipment of goods and led to a proliferation of mills and factories.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Later, a dense network of railroads furthered the region's industry and commerce.
[src:boston/boston-p01] During this period, Boston also flourished culturally.
[src:boston/boston-p01] It was admired for its rarefied literary life and generous artistic patronage.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Members of old Boston families, later dubbed "Boston Brahmins", came to be regarded as the nation's social and cultural elites.
[src:boston/boston-p01] They are often associated with the American upper class, Harvard University, and the Episcopal Church.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Boston was a prominent port of the Atlantic slave trade in the New England Colonies, but was soon overtaken by Salem, Massachusetts, and Newport, Rhode Island.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Boston eventually became a center of the American abolitionist movement.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The city reacted largely negatively to the Fugitive Slave Act of 1850, contributing to President Franklin Pierce's attempt to make an example of Boston after Anthony Burns's attempt to escape to freedom.
[src:boston/boston-p01] In 1822, the citizens of Boston voted to change the official name from the "Town of Boston" to the "City of Boston", and on March 19, 1822, the people of Boston accepted the charter incorporating the city.
[src:boston/boston-p01] At the time Boston was chartered as a city, the population was about 46,226, while the area of the city was only 4.8 sq mi (12 km2).
[src:boston/boston-p01] In the 1820s, Boston's population grew rapidly, and the city's ethnic composition changed dramatically with the first wave of European immigrants.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Irish immigrants dominated the first wave of newcomers during this period, especially following the Great Famine; by 1850, about 35,000 Irish lived in Boston.
[src:boston/boston-p01] In the latter half of the 19th century, the city saw increasing numbers of Irish, Germans, Lebanese, Syrians, French Canadians, and Russian and Polish Jews settling there.
[src:boston/boston-p01] By the end of the 19th century, Boston's core neighborhoods had become enclaves of ethnically distinct immigrants with their residence yielding lasting cultural change.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Italians became the largest inhabitants of the North End, Irish dominated South Boston and Charlestown, and Russian Jews lived in the West End.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Irish and Italian immigrants brought with them Roman Catholicism.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Currently, Catholics make up Boston's largest religious community, and the Irish have played a major role in Boston politics since the early 20th century; prominent figures include the Kennedys, Tip O'Neill, and John F.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Between 1631 and 1890, the city tripled its area through land reclamation by filling in marshes, mud flats, and gaps between wharves along the waterfront.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Reclamation projects in the middle of the 19th century created significant parts of the South End, the West End, the Financial District, and Chinatown.
[src:boston/boston-p01] After the Great Boston Fire of 1872, workers used building rubble as landfill along the downtown waterfront.
[src:boston/boston-p01] During the mid-to-late 19th century, workers filled almost 600 acres (240 ha) of brackish Charles River marshlands west of Boston Common with gravel brought by rail from the hills of Needham Heights.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Other proposals were unsuccessful for the annexation of Brookline, Cambridge, and Chelsea.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Many architecturally significant buildings were built during the early years of the 20th century: Horticultural Hall, the Tennis and Racquet Club, Isabella Stewart Gardner Museum, Fenway Studios, Jordan Hall, and the Boston Opera House.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The Longfellow Bridge, built in 1906, was mentioned by Robert McCloskey in *Make Way for Ducklings*, describing its "salt and pepper shakers" feature.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Fenway Park, home of the Boston Red Sox, opened in 1912, with the Boston Garden opening in 1928.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Logan International Airport opened on September 8, 1923.
[src:boston/boston-p01] On November 28, 1942, Boston's Cocoanut Grove nightclub was the site of the Cocoanut Grove fire, the deadliest nightclub fire in United States history, killing 492 people and injuring hundreds more.
[src:boston/boston-p01] By the early- to mid-20th century, Boston declined economically as factories became old and obsolete and businesses moved out of the region for cheaper labor elsewhere.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Boston responded by initiating various urban renewal projects, under the direction of the Boston Redevelopment Authority (BRA) established in 1957.
[src:boston/boston-p01] In 1958, BRA initiated a project to improve the historic West End neighborhood.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Extensive demolition was met with strong public opposition, and thousands of families were displaced.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The BRA continued implementing eminent domain projects, including the clearance of the vibrant Scollay Square area for construction of the modernist style Government Center.
[src:boston/boston-p01] In 1965, the Columbia Point Health Center opened in the Dorchester neighborhood, the first Community Health Center in the United States.
[src:boston/boston-p01] It mostly served the massive Columbia Point public housing complex adjoining it, which was built in 1953.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The health center is still in operation and was rededicated in 1990 as the Geiger-Gibson Community Health Center.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The Columbia Point complex itself was redeveloped and revitalized from 1984 to 1990 into a mixed-income residential development called Harbor Point Apartments.
[src:boston/boston-p01] By the 1970s, the city's economy had begun to recover after 30 years of economic downturn.
[src:boston/boston-p01] A large number of high-rises were constructed in the Financial District and in Boston's Back Bay during this period.
[src:boston/boston-p01] This boom continued into the mid-1980s and resumed after a few pauses.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Hospitals such as Massachusetts General Hospital, Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center, and Brigham and Women's Hospital lead the nation in medical innovation and patient care.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Nevertheless, the city experienced conflict starting in 1974 over desegregation busing, which resulted in unrest and violence around public schools throughout the mid-1970s.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Boston has also experienced gentrification in the latter half of the 20th century, with housing prices increasing sharply since the 1990s when the city's rent control regime was struck down by statewide ballot proposition.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Boston is an intellectual, technological, and political center.
[src:boston/boston-p01] However, it has lost some important regional institutions, including the loss to mergers and acquisitions of local financial institutions such as FleetBoston Financial, which was acquired by Charlotte-based Bank of America in 2004.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Boston-based department stores Jordan Marsh and Filene's have both merged into the New York City–based Macy's.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The 1993 acquisition of *The Boston Globe* by *The New York Times* was reversed in 2013 when it was resold to Boston businessman John W.
[src:boston/boston-p01] In 2016, it was announced General Electric would be moving its corporate headquarters from Connecticut to the Seaport District in Boston, joining many other companies in this rapidly developing neighborhood.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The city also saw the completion of the Central Artery/Tunnel Project, known as the Big Dig, in 2007 after many delays and cost overruns.
[src:boston/boston-p01] On April 15, 2013, two Chechen Islamist brothers detonated a pair of bombs near the finish line of the Boston Marathon, killing three people and injuring roughly 264.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The subsequent search for the bombers led to a lock-down of Boston and surrounding municipalities.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The region showed solidarity during this time as symbolized by the slogan *Boston Strong*.
[src:boston/boston-p01] In 2016, Boston briefly shouldered a bid as the U.S. applicant for the 2024 Summer Olympics.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The bid was supported by the mayor and a coalition of business leaders and local philanthropists, but was eventually dropped due to public opposition.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The USOC then selected Los Angeles to be the American candidate with Los Angeles ultimately securing the right to host the 2028 Summer Olympics.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Nevertheless, Boston is one of eleven U.S. cities which will host matches during the 2026 FIFA World Cup, with games taking place at Gillette Stadium.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The city's elevation, as measured at Logan International Airport, is 19 ft (5.8 m) above sea level.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The highest point in Boston is Bellevue Hill at 330 ft (100 m) above sea level, and the lowest point is at sea level.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The city is adjacent to Boston Harbor, an arm of Massachusetts Bay, and by extension, the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Boston is surrounded by the Greater Boston metropolitan region.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The Charles River separates Boston's Allston-Brighton, Fenway-Kenmore and Back Bay neighborhoods from Watertown and Cambridge, and most of Boston from its own Charlestown neighborhood.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The Neponset River forms the boundary between Boston's southern neighborhoods and Quincy and Milton.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The Mystic River separates Charlestown from Chelsea and Everett, and Chelsea Creek and Boston Harbor separate East Boston from Downtown, the North End, and the Seaport.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Boston is sometimes called a "city of neighborhoods" because of the profusion of diverse subsections.
[src:boston/boston-p01] More than two-thirds of inner Boston's modern land area did not exist when the city was founded.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Instead, it was created via the gradual filling in of the surrounding tidal areas over the centuries.
[src:boston/boston-p01] This was accomplished using earth from the leveling or lowering of Boston's three original hills, the "Trimountain", after which Tremont Street is named, and with gravel brought by train from Needham to fill the Back Bay.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Back Bay is home to Christian Science Center, Copley Square, Newbury Street, and New England's two tallest buildings: the John Hancock Tower and the Prudential Center.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Near the John Hancock Tower is the old John Hancock Building with its prominent illuminated beacon, the color of which forecasts the weather.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Downtown and its immediate surroundings (including the Financial District, Government Center, and South Boston) consist largely of low-rise masonry buildings – often federal style and Greek revival – interspersed with modern high-rises.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Back Bay includes many prominent landmarks, such as the Boston Public Library, Trinity Church, single-family homes and wooden/brick multi-family row houses.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The South End Historic District is the largest surviving contiguous Victorian-era neighborhood in the US.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The geography of downtown and South Boston was particularly affected by the Central Artery/Tunnel Project (which ran from 1991 to 2007, and was known unofficially as the "Big Dig").
[src:boston/boston-p01] That project removed the elevated Central Artery and incorporated new green spaces and open areas.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Boston is located within the Boston Basin ecoregion, which is characterized by low and rolling hills with a number of ponds, lakes, and reservoirs.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Forests are mainly transition hardwoods such as oak-hickory mixed with white pine.
[src:boston/boston-p01] As a coastal city built largely on fill, sea-level rise is of major concern to the city government.
[src:boston/boston-p01] A climate action plan from 2019 anticipates 2 ft (1 m) to more than 7 ft (2 m) of sea-level rise in Boston by the end of the 21st century.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Many older buildings in certain areas of Boston are supported by wooden piles driven into the area's fill; these piles remain sound if submerged in water, but are subject to dry rot if exposed to air for long periods.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Groundwater levels have been dropping in many areas of the city, due in part to an increase in the amount of rainwater discharged directly into sewers rather than absorbed by the ground.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The Boston Groundwater Trust coordinates monitoring groundwater levels throughout the city via a network of public and private monitoring wells.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The city developed a climate action plan covering carbon reduction in buildings, transportation, and energy use.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The first such plan was commissioned in 2007, with updates released in 2011, 2014, and 2019.
[src:boston/boston-p01] This plan includes the Building Energy Reporting and Disclosure Ordinance, which requires the city's larger buildings to disclose their yearly energy and water use statistics and to partake in an energy assessment every five years.
[src:boston/boston-p01] A separate initiative, Resilient Boston Harbor, lays out neighborhood-specific recommendations for coastal resilience.
[src:boston/boston-p01] In 2013, Mayor Thomas Menino introduced the Renew Boston Whole Building Incentive which reduces the cost of living in buildings that are deemed energy efficient.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Under the Köppen climate classification (using the −3 °C (27 °F) coldest month isotherm), Boston has ahumid subtropical climate (Köppen *Cfa*)..
[src:boston/boston-p01] If using the 0 °C (32 °F) coldest month isotherm, the city lies within the hot-summer humid continental zone (Köppen *Dfa*).
[src:boston/boston-p01] Winters are cold and stormy, with occasional periods of heavy snow.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Spring and fall are usually cool and mild, with varying conditions dependent on wind direction and the position of the jet stream.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Prevailing wind patterns that blow offshore minimize the influence of the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:boston/boston-p01] In winter, areas near the immediate coast often see more rain than snow, as warm air is sometimes drawn off the Atlantic.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Boston lies at the border between USDA plant hardiness zones 6b (away from the coastline) and 7a (close to the coastline).
[src:boston/boston-p01] Receiving over 2,600 hours of sunshine annually, Boston is one of the sunniest oceanic cities located at its latitude globally.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The warmest month is July, with a mean temperature of 74.1 °F (23.4 °C).
[src:boston/boston-p01] The coldest month is January, with a mean temperature of 29.9 °F (−1.2 °C).
[src:boston/boston-p01] Periods exceeding 90 °F (32 °C) in summer and below freezing in winter are not uncommon but tend to be fairly short, with about 13 and 25 days per year seeing each, respectively.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Despite average winter temperatures near freezing, Boston can see entire winters without sustained periods of sub-freezing afternoons.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The winter of 2001-2002 recorded only two days entirely below freezing, with no day with a daily maximum temperature below 29 °F (−2 °C).
[src:boston/boston-p01] The winter of 2023-2024 saw the yearly minimum temperature not falling below 14 °F (−10 °C) that winter.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Sub- 0 °F (−18 °C) readings usually occur every 3 to 5 years.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The most recent sub- 0 °F (−18 °C) reading occurred on February 4, 2023, when the temperature dipped down to −10 °F (−23 °C).
[src:boston/boston-p01] This was the lowest temperature reading in Boston since 1957.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Several decades may pass between 100 °F (38 °C) readings.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The last such reading occurred on June 24, 2025.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Boston's average window for freezing temperatures is November 9 to April 5.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Official temperature records have ranged from −18 °F (−28 °C) on February 9, 1934, up to 104 °F (40 °C) on July 4, 1911.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The record cold daily maximum is 2 °F (−17 °C) on December 30, 1917.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The record warm daily minimum is 83 °F (28 °C) on both August 2, 1975, and July 21, 2019.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The record high dew point is 79 °F (26 °C) recorded on August 10, 2001.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The most humid month on record is August 2018 with an average dewpoint of 66.8 °F (19.3 °C) for the month.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The hottest month on record is July 2019 with an average mean temperature of 78.7 °F (25.9 °C) for the month.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The month with the record warmest daily minimums was July 2019 with an average daily minimum of 70.7 °F (21.5 °C).
[src:boston/boston-p01] Boston has recorded entire months in summer without nighttime lows below 63 °F (17 °C), the record most recently tied in August 2022 and previously set in July 2011 and July 2019.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Summer in Boston can also see entire months without dewpoints below 53 °F (12 °C), with the most recent occurrence being July 2008.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Boston has not recorded a summer since records began without at least one daily minimum of at least 69 °F (21 °C) or higher, and a dewpoint of 71 °F (22 °C) or greater.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The summers where the yearly maximum dew point topped out at 71 °F (22 °C) were in 1974 and 1982; and the yearly maximum daily minimum temperature at 69 °F (21 °C) in 1889.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The average yearly maximum daily minimum temperature is 76.9 °F (24.9 °C), and the average yearly maximum dew point is 75.4 °F (24.1 °C).
[src:boston/boston-p01] Boston averages 43.6 in (1,110 mm) of precipitation a year, with 49.2 in (125 cm) of snowfall per season.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Most snowfall occurs from mid-November to early April.
[src:boston/boston-p01] There is high year-to-year variability in snowfall.
[src:boston/boston-p01] For instance, the winter of 2011–12 saw only 9.3 in (23.6 cm) of accumulating snow, but the previous winter, the corresponding figure was 81.0 in (206 cm).
[src:boston/boston-p01] Boston's coastal location on the North Atlantic makes the city very prone to nor'easters, which can produce large amounts of snow and rain.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Fog is relatively common, particularly in spring and early summer.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Due to its coastal location, Boston often receives sea breezes, especially in the late spring, when water temperatures are still quite cold and temperatures at the coast can be more than 20 °F (11 °C) colder than a few miles inland, sometimes dropping by that amount near midday.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Thunderstorms typically occur from May to September.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Occasionally, they can become severe, with large hail, damaging winds, and heavy downpours.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Although downtown Boston has never been struck by a violent tornado, Boston has experienced many tornado warnings.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Damaging storms are more common to areas north, west, and northwest of the city.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:boston/boston-p01] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:boston/boston-p01] In the 2020 census, Boston was estimated to have 691,531 residents living in 266,724 households—a 12% population increase over 2010.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Boston is the third-most densely populated large U.S. city of over half a million residents, and the most densely populated state capital.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Some 1.2 million persons may be within Boston's boundaries during work hours, and as many as 2 million during special events.
[src:boston/boston-p01] This fluctuation of people is caused by hundreds of thousands of suburban residents who travel to the city for work, education, health care, and special events.
[src:boston/boston-p01] For every 100 females, there were 92.0 males.
[src:boston/boston-p01] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 89.9 males.
[src:boston/boston-p01] There were 252,699 households, of which 20.4% had children under the age of 18 living in them, 25.5% were married couples living together, 16.3% had a female householder with no husband present, and 54.0% were non-families.
[src:boston/boston-p01] 37.1% of all households were made up of individuals, and 9.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The average household size was 2.26 and the average family size was 3.08.
[src:boston/boston-p01] In 2024, the median household income in Boston was $97,791, while the median income for a family was $110,710.
[src:boston/boston-p01] In 2011, full-time year-round male workers had a median income of $52,544 versus $46,540 for full-time year-round female workers.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The per capita income for the city was $33,158.
[src:boston/boston-p01] 21.4% of the population and 16.0% of families were below the poverty line.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Of the total population, 28.8% of those under the age of 18 and 20.4% of those 65 and older were living below the poverty line.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Boston has a significant racial wealth gap with White Bostonians having a median net worth of $247,500 compared to an $8 median net worth for non-immigrant Black residents and $0 for Dominican immigrant residents.
[src:boston/boston-p01] From the 1950s to the end of the 20th century, the proportion of non-Hispanic Whites in Boston declined.
[src:boston/boston-p01] In 2000, non-Hispanic Whites were 49.5% of Boston's population, making the city majority minority for the first time.
[src:boston/boston-p01] In the 21st century, Boston has experienced significant gentrification, during which affluent Whites have moved into formerly non-White areas.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Census Bureau estimated non-Hispanic Whites again formed a slight majority.
[src:boston/boston-p01] By 2010, in part due to a crash in housing prices, as well as increased efforts to make affordable housing more available, the non-White population had rebounded and non-Hispanic White residents formed 47% of the population.
[src:boston/boston-p01] constitute the largest ethnicity in Boston.
[src:boston/boston-p01] In 2011, African-Americans comprised 22% of the city's population.
[src:boston/boston-p01] People of Irish descent formed the second-largest single ethnic group in the city, making up 15.8% of the population, followed by Italians, accounting for 8.3% of the population.
[src:boston/boston-p01] People of West Indian and Caribbean ancestry are another sizable group, collectively at over 15%.
[src:boston/boston-p01] In Greater Boston, these numbers grew significantly, with 150,000 Dominicans according to 2018 estimates, 134,000 Puerto Ricans, 57,500 Salvadorans, 39,000 Guatemalans, 36,000 Mexicans, and over 35,000 Colombians.
[src:boston/boston-p01] East Boston has a diverse Hispanic/Latino population of Salvadorans, Colombians, Guatemalans, Mexicans, Dominicans and Puerto Ricans.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Hispanic populations in southwest Boston neighborhoods are mainly made up of Dominicans and Puerto Ricans, usually sharing neighborhoods in this section with African Americans and Blacks with origins from the Caribbean and Africa especially Cape Verdeans and Haitians.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Neighborhoods such as Jamaica Plain and Roslindale have a growing number of Dominican Americans.
[src:boston/boston-p01] There is a large and historical Armenian community in Boston, and the city is home to the Armenian Heritage Park.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Over 27,000 Chinese Americans made their home in Boston city proper in 2013.
[src:boston/boston-p01] Data is from the American Community Survey's five-year estimates 2008–2012.
[src:boston/boston-p01] In a 2023-24 study by the Pew Research Center, 47% of the population of the city identified themselves as Christians, with 21% attending a variety of Protestant churches and 24% professing Roman Catholic beliefs.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The remaining 13% are composed of adherents of Judaism, Buddhism, Islam, Hinduism, and other faiths.
[src:boston/boston-p01] In 2010, the Catholic Church had the highest number of adherents as a single denomination in the Greater Boston area, with more than two million members and 339 churches, followed by the Episcopal Church with 58,000 adherents in 160 churches.
[src:boston/boston-p01] The United Church of Christ had 55,000 members and 213 churches.
[src:boston/boston-p01] In 2015, the Boston metro area had a Jewish population of approximately 248,000.
[src:boston/boston-p01] More than half the Jewish households in the Greater Boston area reside in the city itself, Brookline, Newton, Cambridge, Somerville, or adjacent towns.
[src:boston/boston-p01] A small minority practices Confucianism, and some practice Boston Confucianism, an American evolution of Confucianism adapted for Boston intellectuals.
[src:boston/boston-p02] A global city, Boston is ranked among the top 30 most economically powerful cities in the world.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Encompassing $610 billion, the Greater Boston metropolitan area has the eighth-largest economy in the country and 16th-largest in the world.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston's colleges and universities exert a significant impact on the regional economy.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston attracts more than 350,000 college students from around the world, who contribute more than US$4.8 billion annually to the city's economy.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The area's schools are major employers and attract industries to the city and surrounding region.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The city is home to a number of technology companies and is a hub for biotechnology, with the Milken Institute rating Boston as the top life sciences cluster in the country.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston receives the highest absolute amount of annual funding from the National Institutes of Health of all cities in the United States.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston is considered highly innovative for a variety of reasons, including the presence of academia, access to venture capital, and the presence of many high-tech companies.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The Route 128 corridor and Greater Boston continue to be a major center for venture capital investment, and high technology remains an important sector.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Tourism composes a large part of Boston's economy, with 21.2 million domestic and international visitors spending $8.3 billion in 2011.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Excluding visitors from Canada and Mexico, over 1.4 million international tourists visited Boston in 2014, with those from China and the United Kingdom leading the list.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston's status as a state capital as well as the regional home of federal agencies has rendered law and government to be another major component of the city's economy.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston is a major seaport along the East Coast of the United States and the oldest continuously operated industrial and fishing port in the Western Hemisphere.
[src:boston/boston-p02] In the 2018 Global Financial Centres Index, Boston was ranked as having the 13th-most competitive financial services center in the world and the second-most competitive in the United States.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston-based Fidelity Investments helped popularize the mutual fund in the 1980s and has made Boston one of the top financial centers in the United States and a center for venture capital firms.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston is home to the headquarters of Santander Bank and State Street Corporation, the latter specializing in asset management and custody services.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston is a printing and publishing center—Houghton Mifflin Harcourt is headquartered within the city, along with Bedford-St.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Pearson PLC publishing units employ several hundred people in Boston.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston is home to two convention centers—the Hynes Convention Center in the Back Bay and the Boston Convention and Exhibition Center on the South Boston waterfront.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston is home to the headquarters of several major athletic and footwear companies including Converse, New Balance, and Reebok.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Rockport, Puma and Wolverine World Wide, Inc. headquarters or regional offices are just outside the city.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston Public Schools enroll 57,000 students attending 145 schools, including Boston Latin Academy, John D.
[src:boston/boston-p02] O'Bryant School of Math & Science, and the Boston Latin School.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The Boston Latin School was established in 1635 and is the oldest public high school in the US.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston also operates the United States' second-oldest public high school and its oldest public elementary school.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The system's students are 40% Hispanic or Latino, 35% Black or African American, 13% White, and 9% Asian.
[src:boston/boston-p02] There are private, parochial, and charter schools.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Approximately 3,300 minority students attend participating suburban schools through the Metropolitan Educational Opportunity Council.
[src:boston/boston-p02] In September 2019, the city began Boston Saves, a program that provides every child enrolled in the city's kindergarten system a savings account, containing $50 to be used toward college or career training.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Several of the highest-ranked universities in the world are near Boston.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Three universities with a major presence in the city, Harvard, MIT, and Tufts, are just outside of Boston in the cities of Cambridge and Somerville, known as the *Brainpower Triangle*.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Harvard is the nation's oldest institute of higher education and is centered across the Charles River in Cambridge, though the majority of its land holdings and a substantial amount of its educational activities are in Boston.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Its business school and athletics facilities are in Boston's Allston neighborhood, and its medical, dental, and public health schools are located in the Longwood area.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) originated in Boston and was long known as "Boston Tech"; it moved across the river to Cambridge in 1916.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Tufts University's main campus is north of the city in Somerville and Medford, though its medical and dental schools are located in Boston's Chinatown at Tufts Medical Center.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Greater Boston has more than 50 colleges and universities, with 250,000 students enrolled in Boston and Cambridge alone.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston's only public university is the University of Massachusetts Boston on Columbia Point in Dorchester.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Roxbury Community College and Bunker Hill Community College are the city's two public community colleges.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Altogether, Boston's colleges and universities employ more than 42,600 people, accounting for nearly seven percent of the city's workforce.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Five members of the Association of American Universities are in Greater Boston, more than any other metropolitan area: Harvard University, the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Tufts University, Boston University, and Brandeis University.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Greater Boston contains seven Highest Research Activity (R1) Universities as per the Carnegie Classification.
[src:boston/boston-p02] This includes, in addition to the aforementioned five, Boston College, and Northeastern University.
[src:boston/boston-p02] This is, by a large margin, the highest concentration of such institutions in a single metropolitan area.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Hospitals, universities, and research institutions in Greater Boston received more than $1.77 billion in National Institutes of Health grants in 2013, more money than any other American metropolitan area.
[src:boston/boston-p02] This high density of research institutes also contributes to Boston's high density of early career researchers, which, due to high housing costs in the region, have been shown to face housing stress.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The region is home to several conservatories and art schools, including the New England Conservatory (the oldest independent conservatory in the United States), the Boston Conservatory, and Berklee College of Music, which has made Boston an important city for jazz music.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Many trade schools also exist in the city such as the Boston Career Institute, the North Bennet Street School, and Greater Boston Joint Apprentice Training Center.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston has a strong mayor–council government system in which the mayor, elected every fourth year, has extensive executive power.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Michelle Wu became mayor in November 2021, succeeding Kim Janey who became the Acting Mayor in March 2021 following Marty Walsh's confirmation to the position of Secretary of Labor in the Biden/Harris Administration.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Walsh's predecessor Thomas Menino's twenty-year tenure was the longest in Boston's history.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The Boston City Council is elected every two years.
[src:boston/boston-p02] There are nine district seats, and four citywide "at-large" seats.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The School Committee, which oversees the Boston Public Schools, is appointed by the mayor.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston uses an algorithm called CityScore to measure the effectiveness of city services.
[src:boston/boston-p02] This score is available on a public online dashboard and allows city managers in police, fire, schools, emergency management services, and 3-1-1 to take action and make adjustments in areas of concern.
[src:boston/boston-p02] As the capital of Massachusetts, Boston plays a major role in state politics.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston has several federal facilities, including the John F.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Kennedy Federal Office Building, the Thomas P.
[src:boston/boston-p02] McCormack Post Office and Courthouse, and the Federal Reserve Bank of Boston.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The United States Court of Appeals for the First Circuit and the United States District Court for the District of Massachusetts are housed in The John Joseph Moakley United States Courthouse.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Federally, Boston is split between two congressional districts.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Three-fourths of Boston is in the 7th district and is represented by Ayanna Pressley.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The remaining southern fourth is in the 8th district and is represented by Stephen Lynch.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Both are Democrats; a Republican has not represented a significant portion of Boston in over a century.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The state's senior member of the United States Senate is Democrat Elizabeth Warren, first elected in 2012.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The state's junior member of the United States Senate is Democrat Ed Markey, who was elected in 2013 to succeed John Kerry after Kerry's appointment and confirmation as the United States Secretary of State.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston included $414 million in spending on the Boston Police Department in the fiscal 2021 budget.
[src:boston/boston-p02] This is the second largest allocation of funding by the city after the allocation to Boston Public Schools.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Like many major American cities, Boston has experienced a great reduction in violent crime since the early 1990s.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston's low crime rate since the 1990s has been credited to the Boston Police Department's collaboration with neighborhood groups and church parishes to prevent youths from joining gangs, as well as involvement from the United States Attorney and District Attorney's offices.
[src:boston/boston-p02] This helped lead in part to what has been touted as the "Boston Miracle".
[src:boston/boston-p02] Murders in Boston dropped from 152 in 1990, a murder rate of 26.5 per 100,000 people, to 31—not one of them a juvenile—in 1999, for a murder rate of 5.26 per 100,000.
[src:boston/boston-p02] According to the Uniform Crime Reporting (UCR) program in 2022, Boston had 3,955 reported violent crimes, which include homicide, rape, robbery, and aggravated assault, and 11,514 reported property crimes, which include arson, burglary, larceny-theft, and motor vehicle theft.
[src:boston/boston-p02] With a violent crime rate of 608.7 per 100,000 people, the city's violent crime rate is higher than Massachusetts' rate of 322 per 100,000 people and the national rate of 380.7 per 100,000 people.
[src:boston/boston-p02] While Boston's property crime rate, at 1,772.0 per 100,000 people, is higher than Massachusetts' property crime rate of 1,070.1 per 100,000 people, it is lower than the national property crime rate of 1,954.4 per 100,000 people.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston shares many cultural roots with greater New England, including a dialect of the non-rhotic Eastern New England accent known as the Boston accent and a regional cuisine with a large emphasis on seafood, salt, and dairy products.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston also has its own collection of neologisms known as *Boston slang* and sardonic humor.
[src:boston/boston-p02] In the early 1800s, William Tudor wrote that Boston was "'perhaps the most perfect and certainly the best-regulated democracy that ever existed.
[src:boston/boston-p02] In the 19th century, Ralph Waldo Emerson, Henry David Thoreau, Nathaniel Hawthorne, Margaret Fuller, James Russell Lowell, and Henry Wadsworth Longfellow wrote in Boston.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Some consider the Old Corner Bookstore to be the "cradle of American literature", the place where these writers met and where *The Atlantic Monthly* was first published.
[src:boston/boston-p02] In 1852, the Boston Public Library was founded as the first free library in the United States.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston's literary culture continues today thanks to the city's many universities and the Boston Book Festival.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Music is afforded a high degree of civic support in Boston.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The Boston Symphony Orchestra is one of the "Big Five", a group of the greatest American orchestras, and the classical music magazine *Gramophone* called it one of the "world's best" orchestras.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Symphony Hall (west of Back Bay) is home to the Boston Symphony Orchestra and the related Boston Youth Symphony Orchestra, which is the largest youth orchestra in the nation, and to the Boston Pops Orchestra.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Other concerts are held at the New England Conservatory's Jordan Hall.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The Boston Ballet performs at the Boston Opera House.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Other performing-arts organizations in the city include the Boston Lyric Opera Company, Opera Boston, Boston Baroque (the first permanent Baroque orchestra in the US), and the Handel and Haydn Society (one of the oldest choral companies in the United States).
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston is a center for contemporary classical music with a number of performing groups, several of which are associated with the city's conservatories and universities.
[src:boston/boston-p02] These include the Boston Modern Orchestra Project and Boston Musica Viva.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Several theaters are in or near the Theater District south of Boston Common, including the Cutler Majestic Theatre, Citi Performing Arts Center, the Colonial Theater, and the Orpheum Theatre.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The city is the site of several events during the Fourth of July period.
[src:boston/boston-p02] They include the week-long Harborfest festivities and a Boston Pops concert accompanied by fireworks on the banks of the Charles River.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Several historic sites relating to the American Revolution period are preserved as part of the Boston National Historical Park because of the city's prominent role.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Many are found along the Freedom Trail, which is marked by a red line of bricks embedded in the ground.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The city is home to several art museums and galleries, including the Museum of Fine Arts and Isabella Stewart Gardner Museum.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The Institute of Contemporary Art is housed in a contemporary building designed by Diller Scofidio + Renfro in the Seaport District.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston's South End Art and Design District (SoWa) and Newbury St. are both art gallery destinations.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Columbia Point is the location of the University of Massachusetts Boston, the Edward M.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Kennedy Institute for the United States Senate, the John F.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Kennedy Presidential Library and Museum, and the Massachusetts Archives and Commonwealth Museum.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The Boston Athenæum (one of the oldest independent libraries in the United States), Boston Children's Museum, Bull & Finch Pub (whose building is known from the television show *Cheers*), Museum of Science, and the New England Aquarium are within the city.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston has been a noted religious center from its earliest days.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Boston serves nearly 300 parishes and is based in the Cathedral of the Holy Cross (1875) in the South End, while the Episcopal Diocese of Massachusetts serves just under 200 congregations, with the Cathedral Church of St.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Unitarian Universalism has its headquarters in the Fort Point neighborhood.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The Christian Scientists are headquartered in Back Bay at the Mother Church (1894).
[src:boston/boston-p02] The oldest church in Boston is First Church in Boston, founded in 1630.
[src:boston/boston-p02] King's Chapel was the city's first Anglican church, founded in 1686 and converted to Unitarianism in 1785.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Other churches include Old South Church (1669), Christ Church (better known as Old North Church, 1723), the oldest church building in the city, Trinity Church (1733), Park Street Church (1809), and Basilica and Shrine of Our Lady of Perpetual Help on Mission Hill (1878).
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston has teams in the four major North American men's professional sports leagues plus Major League Soccer.
[src:boston/boston-p02] As of 2024, the city has won 40 championships in these leagues.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The Boston Red Sox, a founding member of the American League of Major League Baseball in 1901, play their home games at Fenway Park, near Kenmore Square, in the city's Fenway section.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Built in 1912, it is the oldest sports arena or stadium in active use in the United States among the four major professional American sports leagues, Major League Baseball, the National Football League, National Basketball Association, and the National Hockey League.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston was the site of the first game of the first modern World Series, in 1903.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The series was played between the AL Champion Boston Americans and the NL champion Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Persistent reports that the team was known in 1903 as the "Boston Pilgrims" appear to be unfounded.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston's first professional baseball team was the Red Stockings, one of the charter members of the National Association in 1871, and of the National League in 1876.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The team played under that name until 1883, under the name Beaneaters until 1911, and under the name Braves from 1912 until they moved to Milwaukee after the 1952 season.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Since 1966 they have played in Atlanta as the Atlanta Braves.
[src:boston/boston-p02] TD Garden, formerly called the FleetCenter and built to replace the since-demolished Boston Garden, is above North Station and is the home of two major league teams: the Boston Bruins of the National Hockey League and the Boston Celtics of the National Basketball Association.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The Bruins were the first American member of the National Hockey League and an Original Six franchise.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The Boston Celtics were founding members of the Basketball Association of America, one of the two leagues that merged to form the NBA.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The Celtics have won eighteen championships, the most of any NBA team.
[src:boston/boston-p02] While they have played in suburban Foxborough since 1971, the New England Patriots of the National Football League were founded in 1960 as the Boston Patriots, changing their name after relocating.
[src:boston/boston-p02] They share Gillette Stadium with the New England Revolution of Major League Soccer.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Another team associated with Boston who plays outside the city is the Boston Fleet of the PWHL, which plays at the Tsongas Center in nearby Lowell.
[src:boston/boston-p02] During the inaugural 2024 PWHL playoffs, the Fleet (then simply known as PWHL Boston) made it to the Walter Cup finals, where they lost to the Minnesota Frost (PWHL Minnesota at the time).
[src:boston/boston-p02] The area's many colleges and universities are active in college athletics.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Four NCAA Division I members play in the area—Boston College, Boston University, Harvard University, and Northeastern University.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Of the four, only Boston College participates in college football at the highest level, the Football Bowl Subdivision.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Harvard participates in the second-highest level, the Football Championship Subdivision.
[src:boston/boston-p02] These four universities participate in the Beanpot, an annual men's and women's ice hockey tournament.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The men's Beanpot is hosted at the TD Garden, while the women's Beanpot is held at each member school's home arena on a rotating basis.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston has Esports teams, such as the Overwatch League (OWL)'s Boston Uprising.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Established in 2017, they were the first team to complete a perfect stage with 0 losses.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The Boston Breach is another esports team in the Call of Duty League (CDL).
[src:boston/boston-p02] One of the best-known sporting events in the city is the Boston Marathon, the 26.2 mi (42.2 km) race which is the world's oldest annual marathon, run on Patriots' Day in April.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The Red Sox traditionally play a home game starting around 11 a.m. on the same day, with the early start time allowing fans to watch runners finish the race nearby after the conclusion of the ballgame.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Another major annual event is the Head of the Charles Regatta, held in October.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston Common, near the Financial District and Beacon Hill, is the oldest public park in the United States.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Along with the adjacent Boston Public Garden, it is part of the Emerald Necklace, a string of parks designed by Frederick Law Olmsted to run through the city.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The Emerald Necklace includes the Back Bay Fens, Arnold Arboretum, Jamaica Pond, Boston's largest body of freshwater, and Franklin Park, the city's largest park and home of the Franklin Park Zoo.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Another major park is the Esplanade, along the banks of the Charles River.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The Hatch Shell, an outdoor concert venue, is adjacent to the Charles River Esplanade.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Other parks are scattered throughout the city, with major parks and beaches near Castle Island and the south end, in Charlestown and along the Dorchester, South Boston, and East Boston shorelines.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston's black community is served by the *Bay State Banner*, a newspaper focused on the issues of interest to black Bostonians.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The *Bay State Banner* has operated since 1965.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The city's growing Latino population has given rise to a number of local and regional Spanish-language newspapers.
[src:boston/boston-p02] These include *El Planeta* (owned by the former publisher of the *Boston Phoenix*), *El Mundo*, and *La Semana*.
[src:boston/boston-p02] *Siglo21*, with its main offices in nearby Lawrence, is also widely distributed.
[src:boston/boston-p02] LGBT publications serve Boston's large LGBT (lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender) population such as *The Rainbow Times*, the only minority and lesbian-owned LGBT news magazine.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Founded in 2006, *The Rainbow Times* is now based out of Boston, but serves all of New England.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston is the largest broadcasting market in New England, with the radio market being the ninth largest in the United States.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Several major AM stations include talk radio WRKO, sports/talk station WEEI, and news radio WBZ (AM).
[src:boston/boston-p02] WBZ is a 50,000 watt "clear channel" station whose nighttime broadcasts are heard hundreds of miles from Boston.
[src:boston/boston-p02] A variety of commercial FM radio formats serve the area, as do NPR stations WBUR and WGBH.
[src:boston/boston-p02] College and university radio stations include WERS (Emerson), WHRB (Harvard), WUMB (UMass Boston), WMBR (MIT), WZBC (Boston College), WMFO (Tufts University), WBRS (Brandeis University), WRBB (Northeastern University) and WMLN-FM (Curry College).
[src:boston/boston-p02] The Boston television DMA, which also includes Manchester, New Hampshire, is the eighth largest in the United States.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The city is also home to PBS member station WGBH-TV 2, a major producer of PBS programs, which also operates WGBX 44.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Spanish-language television networks, including UniMás (WUTF-TV 27), Telemundo (WNEU 60, a sister station to WBTS-CD), and Univisión (WUNI 66), have a presence in the region, with WNEU and WUNI serving as network owned-and-operated stations.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Most of the area's television stations have their transmitters in nearby Needham and Newton along the Route 128 corridor.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Seven Boston television stations are carried by satellite television and cable television providers in Canada.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Many of Boston's medical facilities are associated with universities.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The Longwood Medical and Academic Area, adjacent to the Fenway, district, is home to a large number of medical and research facilities, including Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center, Brigham and Women's Hospital, Boston Children's Hospital, Dana–Farber Cancer Institute, and Joslin Diabetes Center.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Prominent medical facilities, including Massachusetts General Hospital, Massachusetts Eye and Ear Infirmary and Spaulding Rehabilitation Hospital are in the Beacon Hill area.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Many of the facilities in Longwood and near Massachusetts General Hospital are affiliated with Harvard Medical School.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Tufts Medical Center (formerly Tufts-New England Medical Center), in the southern portion of the Chinatown neighborhood, is affiliated with Tufts University School of Medicine.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston Medical Center, in the South End neighborhood, is the region's largest safety-net hospital and trauma center.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Formed by the merger of Boston City Hospital, the first municipal hospital in the United States, and Boston University Hospital, Boston Medical Center now serves as the primary teaching facility for the Boston University School of Medicine.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston Medical Center – Brighton (formerly St.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Elizabeth's Medical Center) is located in the Brighton neighborhood.
[src:boston/boston-p02] New England Baptist Hospital is in Mission Hill.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The city has Veterans Affairs medical centers in the Jamaica Plain and West Roxbury neighborhoods.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Logan International Airport, in East Boston and operated by the Massachusetts Port Authority (Massport), is Boston's principal airport.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Nearby general aviation airports are Beverly Regional Airport and Lawrence Municipal Airport to the north, Hanscom Field to the west, and Norwood Memorial Airport to the south.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Massport also operates several major facilities within the Port of Boston, including a cruise ship terminal and facilities to handle bulk and container cargo in South Boston, and other facilities in Charlestown and East Boston.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Downtown Boston's streets grew organically, so they do not form a planned grid, unlike those in later-developed Back Bay, East Boston, the South End, and South Boston.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston is the eastern terminus of I-90, which in Massachusetts runs along the Massachusetts Turnpike.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The Central Artery follows I-93 as the primary north–south artery that carries most of the through traffic in Downtown Boston.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Other major highways include US 1, which carries traffic to the North Shore and areas south of Boston, US 3, which connects to the northwestern suburbs, MA 3, which connects to the South Shore and Cape Cod, and MA 2 which connects to the western suburbs.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Surrounding the city is MA 128, a partial beltway which has been largely subsumed by other routes (mostly I-95 and I-93).
[src:boston/boston-p02] With nearly a third of Bostonians using public transit for their commute to work, Boston has the sixth-highest rate of public transit usage in the country.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The city of Boston has a higher than average percentage of households without a car.
[src:boston/boston-p02] In 2016, 33.8 percent of Boston households lacked a car, compared with the national average of 8.7 percent.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The city averaged 0.94 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston's public transportation agency, the Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority (MBTA), operates the oldest underground rapid transit system in the Americas and is the fourth-busiest rapid transit system in the country, with 65.5 mi (105 km) of track on four lines.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The MBTA also operates busy bus, commuter rail, and ferry networks.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Amtrak intercity rail to Boston is provided through four stations: South Station, North Station, Back Bay, and Route 128.
[src:boston/boston-p02] South Station is a major intermodal transportation hub and is the terminus of Amtrak's *Northeast Regional*, *Acela Express*, and *Lake Shore Limited* routes, in addition to multiple MBTA services.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Back Bay is also served by MBTA and those three Amtrak routes, while Route 128, in the southwestern suburbs of Boston, is only served by the *Acela Express* and *Northeast Regional*.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Meanwhile, Amtrak's *Downeaster* to Brunswick, Maine terminates in North Station, and is the only Amtrak route to do so.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Nicknamed "The Walking City", Boston hosts more pedestrian commuters than do other comparably populated cities.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Owing to factors such as necessity, the compactness of the city and large student population, 13 percent of the population commutes by foot, making it the highest percentage of pedestrian commuters in the country out of the major American cities.
[src:boston/boston-p02] As of 2024, Walk Score ranks Boston as the third most walkable U.S. city, with a Walk Score of 83, a Transit Score of 72, and a Bike Score of 69.
[src:boston/boston-p02] Boston has one of the highest rates of bicycle commuting.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The bikeshare program Bluebikes, originally called Hubway, launched in late July 2011.
[src:boston/boston-p02] The system has 480 stations with a total of 4,500 bikes.
[src:boston/boston-p02] PBSC Urban Solutions provides bicycles and technology for this bike-sharing system.
